    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i was thinking it might be something electrical since it's just a steady hum. is there a specific part that usually fails when the motor is powered but the fan stays still? also what should i look for if i do open the panel up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A steady hum can be a good indicator of an electrical issue. When the motor is powered but the fan stays still, it's often related to the capacitor or the contactor. The capacitor stores energy and helps to start the motor, but if it's failing, the motor might not be able to engage the fan. The contactor, on the other hand, is responsible for switching the power to the motor. If it's malfunctioning, the motor might spin, but the fan won't move.\n\nIf you do decide to open the panel, be sure to unplug the unit first, and look for signs of wear or corrosion on the contactor and capacitor. You might also want to check the wiring and connections for any signs of damage or overheating. It's also a good idea to check the capacitor's voltage rating and look for any signs of leakage. If you're not comfortable with DIY repairs or if you're unsure about what you're looking at, it's always best to call a professional.",
