    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it sounds like it might be the capacitor then. if i find it's swollen or leaking, can i just swap it out myself? also why does it hum if it's not actually moving anything?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A swollen or leaking capacitor is a common culprit when it comes to humming AC units. If you're comfortable with DIY repairs, you can try swapping it out yourself. Just be sure to follow proper safety precautions when handling electrical components, and make sure to purchase a replacement capacitor with the same specifications as the original.\n\nAs for the humming, it's often due to the capacitor's residual energy. When the capacitor is connected to the motor, it stores energy that's released as the motor starts to spin. Even if the fan isn't moving, the capacitor is still holding onto that energy, which can cause the humming noise. It's a bit like a leftover echo of the motor's startup process, if you will. The humming can be quite loud, but it's usually not a cause for concern. However, if the capacitor is leaking or swollen, it can cause the humming to become more pronounced or even lead to a complete failure of the unit.",
